Notebook[{

Cell[CellGroupData[{
Cell["Chapter 2  -  Section 2.2", "Title"],

Cell[TextData[{
  StyleBox["In this ",
    FontWeight->"Bold"],
  StyleBox["Mathematica",
    FontWeight->"Bold",
    FontSlant->"Italic"],
  StyleBox[" notebook, you will explore hazards associated with solutions in \
implicit form and in numerical form.  \n",
    FontWeight->"Bold"],
  "\n",
  StyleBox["In most cases, to adapt this code to other problems, you will \
have to change only the input shown in red. Throughout this notebook, you may \
ignore the warnings about possible spelling errors. To open a cell grouping, \
double-click on the right-hand side of the double cell marker.",
    FontSize->14]
}], "Subsubtitle"],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell[TextData[{
  "Problem",
  " 21:   y' = ",
  Cell[BoxData[
      \(TraditionalForm\`\(1\  + \ 3  x\^2\)\/\(3  y\^2\  - \ 6  y\)\)]]
}], "Section"],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["Implicit Solution by Integration and Implicit Plot", "Subsection"],

Cell["\<\
We will separate the variables and integrate both sides. We will use the \
initial condition for bounds on the integrals.\
\>", "Text"],

Cell[BoxData[{
    RowBox[{"lhs", ":=", 
      RowBox[{
        StyleBox[\(\[Integral]\_1\%y\),
          FontColor->RGBColor[1, 0, 0]], 
        RowBox[{
          StyleBox[\((3  y\^2 - 6  y)\),
            FontColor->RGBColor[1, 0, 
            0]], \(\[DifferentialD]y\)}]}]}], "\[IndentingNewLine]", 
    RowBox[{"rhs", ":=", 
      RowBox[{
        StyleBox[\(\[Integral]\_0\%x\),
          FontColor->RGBColor[1, 0, 0]], 
        RowBox[{
          StyleBox[\((1 + 3  x\^2)\),
            FontColor->RGBColor[1, 0, 
            0]], \(\[DifferentialD]x\)}]}]}], "\[IndentingNewLine]", \
\(equation = lhs \[Equal] rhs\)}], "Input"],

Cell["\<\
If you have not loaded this graphics package yet, do so at this time.\
\>", "Text"],

Cell[BoxData[
    \(<< Graphics`ImplicitPlot`\)], "Input"],

Cell[BoxData[{
    RowBox[{
      RowBox[{"xmin", "=", 
        StyleBox[\(-10\),
          FontColor->RGBColor[1, 0, 0]]}], ";", " ", 
      RowBox[{"xmax", "=", 
        StyleBox[" ",
          FontColor->RGBColor[1, 0, 0]], 
        StyleBox["10",
          FontColor->RGBColor[1, 0, 0]]}], ";", " ", 
      RowBox[{"ymin", "=", 
        StyleBox[\(-10\),
          FontColor->RGBColor[1, 0, 0]]}], ";", " ", 
      RowBox[{"ymax", "=", 
        StyleBox["10",
          FontColor->RGBColor[1, 0, 0]]}], 
      ";"}], "\[IndentingNewLine]", \(ImplicitPlot[
      equation, {x, xmin, xmax}, {y, ymin, ymax}, 
      AxesLabel \[Rule] {x, y}]\)}], "Input"],

Cell["\<\
You may change the values of the bounds to see the solution over a larger \
interval. There may be vertical tangents at two locations on either side of x \
= 0. We will look more closely at these by reducing our domain and range and \
we will plot this in blue..\
\>", "Text"],

Cell[BoxData[{
    RowBox[{
      RowBox[{"xmin", "=", 
        StyleBox[\(-3\),
          FontColor->RGBColor[1, 0, 0]]}], ";", " ", 
      RowBox[{"xmax", "=", 
        StyleBox["3",
          FontColor->RGBColor[1, 0, 0]]}], ";", " ", 
      RowBox[{"ymin", "=", 
        StyleBox[\(-3\),
          FontColor->RGBColor[1, 0, 0]]}], ";", " ", 
      RowBox[{"ymax", "=", 
        StyleBox["3",
          FontColor->RGBColor[1, 0, 0]]}], 
      ";"}], "\[IndentingNewLine]", \(pim = 
      ImplicitPlot[equation, {x, xmin, xmax}, {y, ymin, ymax}, 
        AxesLabel \[Rule] {x, y}, 
        PlotStyle \[Rule] {RGBColor[0, 0, 1], {Thickness[ .01]}}]\)}], "Input"]
}, Closed]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["Numerical Solutions with Explicit Plot", "Subsection"],

Cell["\<\
To solve differential equations numerically, we must have an initial \
condition and when the independent variable is specified, an interval  \
extending beyond the initial condition must also be specified.\
\>", "Text"],

Cell[BoxData[{\(Clear[x, y]\), "\[IndentingNewLine]", 
    RowBox[{
      RowBox[{"yprime", "=", 
        StyleBox[\(\(1 + 3  x\^2\)\/\(3  y[x]\^2 - 6  y[x]\)\),
          FontColor->RGBColor[1, 0, 0]]}], ";"}], "\[IndentingNewLine]", 
    RowBox[{
      RowBox[{\({a, b}\), "=", 
        RowBox[{"{", 
          StyleBox[\(0, 1\),
            FontColor->RGBColor[1, 0, 0]], "}"}]}], 
      ";"}], "\[IndentingNewLine]", \(ynum1 = 
      NDSolve[{\(y'\)[x] \[Equal] yprime, y[a] \[Equal] b}, 
        y[x], {x, a, xmax}]\), "\[IndentingNewLine]", \(ynum2 = 
      NDSolve[{\(y'\)[x] \[Equal] yprime, y[a] \[Equal] b}, 
        y[x], {x, a, xmin}]\)}], "Input"],

Cell["\<\
The warning messages here ate very important. It tells us that the numerical \
solution technique has run into a problem near x = 1 and x = -1. So, the \
numerical solutions only extend from x = 0 to |x| = 1. Let's look at the \
plot.\
\>", "Text"],

Cell[BoxData[{
    RowBox[{"pn1", "=", 
      RowBox[{"Plot", "[", 
        RowBox[{\(y[x] /. ynum1\), ",", 
          RowBox[{"{", 
            RowBox[{"x", ",", 
              StyleBox["0",
                FontColor->RGBColor[1, 0, 0]], ",", 
              StyleBox["1",
                FontColor->RGBColor[1, 0, 0]]}], "}"}], 
          ",", \(PlotStyle \[Rule] {RGBColor[1, 0, 0], {Thickness[ .01]}}\), 
          ",", " ", \(AxesLabel \[Rule] {x, y}\)}], 
        "]"}]}], "\[IndentingNewLine]", 
    RowBox[{"pn2", "=", 
      RowBox[{"Plot", "[", 
        RowBox[{\(y[x] /. ynum2\), ",", 
          RowBox[{"{", 
            RowBox[{"x", ",", 
              StyleBox[\(-1\),
                FontColor->RGBColor[1, 0, 0]], ",", 
              StyleBox["0",
                FontColor->RGBColor[1, 0, 0]]}], "}"}], 
          ",", \(PlotStyle \[Rule] {RGBColor[1, 0, 0], {Thickness[ .01]}}\), 
          ",", " ", \(AxesLabel \[Rule] {x, y}\)}], "]"}]}]}], "Input"],

Cell["\<\
You could explore the numerical solution for different initial conditions as \
well.\
\>", "Text"]
}, Closed]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["Analysis of the Analytical and Numerical Solutions", "Subsection"],

Cell[BoxData[
    \(Show[pim, pn1, pn2, PlotRange \[Rule] {ymin, ymax}]\)], "Input"],

Cell["\<\
This is a good example of a limitation when you use numerical methods to \
solve a differential equation. In the numerical solution, it is sort of like \
we fell off a cliff! However, there are many differential equations for which \
we cannot find an analytical solution, implicitly or explicitly. In those \
cases, we rely on graphical analyses of direction fields and numerical \
solutions.\
\>", "Text"],

Cell["\<\
Suppose we plot the direction field for this differential equation, together \
with its solution curves. First we need to load a graphics package.\
\>", "Text"],

Cell[BoxData[
    \(<< Graphics`PlotField`\)], "Input"],

Cell["\<\
For our input, we will use the coefficients for dx and dy, respectively, from \
the original differential equation after the variables have been separated.\
\>", "Text"],

Cell[BoxData[
    RowBox[{"pd", "=", 
      RowBox[{"PlotVectorField", "[", 
        RowBox[{
          RowBox[{"{", 
            RowBox[{
              StyleBox[\((1 + 3  x\^2)\),
                FontColor->RGBColor[1, 0, 0]], ",", 
              StyleBox[\((3  y\^2 - 6  y)\),
                FontColor->RGBColor[1, 0, 0]]}], "}"}], 
          ",", \({x, xmin, xmax}\), ",", \({y, ymin, ymax}\), ",", 
          " ", \(Axes \[Rule] True\), ",", \(AxesLabel \[Rule] {x, y}\), 
          ",", \(ScaleFactor \[Rule] 1\), ",", \(AspectRatio \[Rule] 1\), 
          ",", \(PlotPoints \[Rule] 30\)}], "]"}]}]], "Input"],

Cell[BoxData[
    \(Show[pim, pn1, pn2, pd, PlotRange \[Rule] {ymin, ymax}]\)], "Input"]
}, Closed]]
}, Open  ]]
}, Open  ]]
},
